## Background and Motivation
Recently JsonIgnoreCondition have been changed to have WhenWritingDefault rather than WhenNull.
See:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5130190/87240149-45a5b100-c417-11ea-8535-2b1ccdbfd61c.png)

When serving JSON for frontends, then default values of value types are extremely important. It's not like null.
You could argue that undefined and null have "similar" semantic in Javascript, so not having the null field serialized makes sense. It will be undefined, and checks you would do against null such as ` if (!value)` will match the undefined behavior too.
While for value types you don't expect that it can become undefined, so you'll end up with subtle bugs after deserialization.

That's why I believe that WhenWritingNull makes a lot of sense.
JSON.NET has a similar feature, see: https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/T_Newtonsoft_Json_NullValueHandling.htm

Remarks:
- I cannot think of deserialization usages that make sense, that's why I proposed WhenWritingNull.
- Options.IgnoreNullValues is not a solution, since it recently became obsolete.

## Proposed API

WhenWritingNull is the new enum entry.

```c#
public enum JsonIgnoreCondition
    {
        /// <summary>
        /// Property is never ignored during serialization or deserialization.
        /// </summary>
        Never = 0,
        /// <summary>
        /// Property is always ignored during serialization and deserialization.
        /// </summary>
        Always = 1,
        /// <summary>
        /// If the value is the default, the property is ignored during serialization.
        /// </summary>
        WhenWritingDefault = 2,
        /// <summary>
        /// If the value is null, the property is ignored during serialization.
        /// </summary>
        WhenWritingNull = 3,
    }
```
While working on a regression for https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/38800 I wrote a PR that fixed both the regression and proposed the change, see here: https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/38811.
That should have been separate PRs, so the PR got rejected, but you can see a baseline there.

## Usage Examples

In global options:

```c#
public class MyClass
{
    public int[] ReferenceType { get; set; }

    public int ValueType { get; set; }
}

[Fact]
public static void Serialize_value_type_but_not_reference_type()
{
    var options = new JsonSerializerOptions
    {
        DefaultIgnoreCondition = JsonIgnoreCondition.WhenNull
    };

    string json = @"{""ReferenceType"":null, ""ValueType"":18}";

    var obj = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<MyClass>(json, options);

    // Deserialize
    Assert.Null(obj.ReferenceType);
    Assert.Equal(18, obj.ValueType);

    // Deserialize
    obj = new MyClass();
    json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(obj, options);
    Assert.Equal(@"{""ValueType"":0}", json);
}
```

On top of properties:

```c#
public class MyClass
{
    [JsonIgnore(Condition = JsonIgnoreCondition.WhenWritingNull)]
    public int[] ReferenceType { get; set; }

    public int ValueType { get; set; }
}

[Fact]
public static void Serialize_value_type_but_not_reference_type()
{
    string json = @"{""ReferenceType"":null, ""ValueType"":18}";

    var obj = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<MyClass>(json);

    // Deserialize
    Assert.Null(obj.ReferenceType);
    Assert.Equal(18, obj.ValueType);

    // Deserialize
    obj = new MyClass();
    json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(obj);
    Assert.Equal(@"{""ValueType"":0}", json);
}
```
